                <head>No. 493.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Evarts</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Baker</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1879-02-24">
                            <hi rend="italic">February</hi> 24, 1879</date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 35.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Your dispatch No. 85, of the 24th ultimo, with a
                    copy of the correspondence between yourself and the minister of foreign affairs
                    of Venezuela, in relation to the resolution of the executive that cargoes
                    destined for Puerto Cabello be discharged at La Guayra, has been received.</p>
                <p>In reply I have to state that your non-acquiescence in the order referred to is
                    approved on the ground that Puerto Cabello was in possession of a force hostile
                    to the government, and consequently was not by such order closed to commerce.
                    Such cases are numerous in the relations of this government with the
                    Spanish-American States.</p>
                <p>I am, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>WILLIAM M. EVARTS.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
